hopobject.name: Page
hopobject.body: I love this site daddyroids.org Sally - 2/10 for history. The growth in the 1820s in industry was largely funded by recycled bad debt from the collapsed property boom during the Napoleonic wars - see Byron 'The Age of Bronze' Canny Quakers loaned money where it would generate real growth, and men like Edward Pease became immensely rich. The Markets produced their usual cycles of boom and bust - 1825, 1846, etc - nothing useful.
